{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 21:49:48.704185", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — SDN spine–leaf lab\n\nSummary (executive):\n- The network is experiencing a clear data-plane outage: host-to-host connectivity within the 10.0.0.0/24 subnets is not functioning.\n- Root cause (most likely): the Open vSwitch (openvswitch-switch) daemon is not running on all three switch nodes (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1). As a result the OVS bridge interfaces are down and switching between host ports and spine/leaf links is not occurring.\n- Impact: Host subnets (10.0.0.0/24) are effectively isolated — pings/flows between hosts fail. The management interfaces (20.0.0.0/24) show addresses assigned, so the switch VMs themselves appear up at the OS level, but their OVS dataplane is inactive.\n\nEvidence and observations\n1) Reachability scan\n- A reachability attempt returned many \"unknown\" status entries for host-to-host pings (get_reachability). The test did not show successful data-plane ping results — consistent with a switching plane failure.\n\n2) Host network configuration (examples)\n- host_1_1: eth0 = 10.0.0.1/24, RX packets: 0, TX packets: 6\n- host_1_2: eth0 = 10.0.0.2/24, RX packets: 0, TX packets: 6\n- host_2_1: eth0 = 10.0.0.9/24, RX packets: 0, TX packets: 6\n- host_2_2: eth0 = 10.0.0.10/24, RX packets: 0, TX packets: 6\n- Interpretation: Hosts have correct IPs on 10.0.0.0/24 but show transmit attempts without receive traffic (no RX), indicating their frames are not being switched/returned.\n\n3) Switch network configuration and state (key findings)\n- leaf_1: output includes a logical bridge interface \"leaf_1\" in state DOWN. The host OS shows a management interface eth12 with inet 20.0.0.5/24 configured.\n- leaf_2: similar — \"leaf_2\" bridge state DOWN, management eth12 = 20.0.0.6/24.\n- spine_1: \"spine_1\" bridge state DOWN; management eth8 = 20.0.0.1/24 and that interface shows RX/TX packets on the OS.\n- Important note: management IPs are present on the switch OS network interfaces (20.0.0.x), so the node OS is alive and reachable at management-layer (potentially). However the OVS bridge devices themselves are reported DOWN.\n\n4) OVS daemon status (definitive)\n- systemctl status openvswitch-switch on leaf_1: Active: inactive (dead)\n- systemctl status openvswitch-switch on leaf_2: Active: inactive (dead)\n- systemctl status openvswitch-switch on spine_1: Active: inactive (dead)\n- Interpretation: the openvswitch-switch service/daemon is not running on all three switch VMs. With the OVS service dead the OVS bridges/forwarding plane do not operate even though physical interfaces and management IPs are present.\n\nLocalization (faulty components)\n- Devices: leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1 (all OVS switch nodes).\n- Fault domain: OVS control/process daemon and resulting OVS bridge dataplane on those nodes.\n- Affected functions: forwarding between host ports and leaf–spine links (the entire L2 switching fabric for the host subnets 10.0.0.0/24). Management network shows interfaces configured (20.0.0.x), so the management plane of switch VMs appears up even though OVS is down.\n\nRoot-cause analysis (most likely)\n- Direct proximate cause: openvswitch-switch service is stopped/inactive on all OVS nodes. When OVS user-space/daemon is not running, the ovs-system bridge and logical bridges are not brought up and packet switching between connected host interfaces and spine/leaf links does not occur.\n- Possible triggers (observational; not proven from current data): OVS crash, manual stop, failed startup, package/service misconfiguration, or resource issue causing the service to exit. (No additional evidence collected here to distinguish which of these caused the service to be inactive.)\n\nSeverity and impact\n- Severity: High for data-plane connectivity among hosts — host-to-host communication on 10.0.0.0/24 is non-functional.\n- Scope: All hosts connected to leaf_1 and leaf_2 (and any flows that must transit spine_1) are impacted because their OVS-based forwarding elements are down.\n- Management-plane impact: Switch OSes retain management IP addresses (20.0.0.x), so the nodes themselves may be reachable for management; however the forwarding plane is non-operational.\n\nRelevant outputs (selected excerpts)\n- openvswitch-switch.service status (leaf_1 / leaf_2 / spine_1): \"Active: inactive (dead)\"\n- leaf_1 ip addr: leaf_1: <...> state DOWN; inet 20.0.0.5/24 on eth12\n- spine_1 ip addr: spine_1: <...> state DOWN; inet 20.0.0.1/24 on eth8\n- host_1_1 ip addr: inet 10.0.0.1/24; RX packets 0 TX packets 6\n\nRecommendations for further diagnosis (if you want to continue gathering evidence)\n- Collect system logs for openvswitch on each switch node (journalctl -u openvswitch-switch, /var/log/openvswitch/) to see why the service is inactive.\n- Run ovs-vsctl show and ovs-ofctl (if OVS runs) to confirm bridge configuration and OpenFlow connection state after service investigation.\n- Confirm controller connectivity (controller at 20.0.0.100) from switch OS to see if controller reachability issues preceded OVS shutdown.\n(Note: these are suggested next-diagnostic steps. I did not perform them because the present evidence already localizes the primary anomaly.)\n\nConclusion\n- The network is anomalous: the OVS forwarding plane is down on all switches. The likely root cause is that the openvswitch-switch service is not running on leaf_1, leaf_2 and spine_1. This results in a widespread data-plane outage for the 10.0.0.0/24 host subnets while the switch OS management interfaces remain configured.\n\nIf you want, I can proceed to:\n- gather logs (journalctl) from the switch nodes to look for crash/restart reasons, or\n- run live connectivity tests (pings) after attempts to restart services (if you request remediation).", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 24401, "output_tokens": 2417, "total_tokens": 26818, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 24192}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 960}}}
